            "content": "# SEC-H2: Enforce `public_host` when node identity is present\n\n## Context\n\n**Issue**: [#68](https://github.com/leon0399/reme/issues/68) — `public_host = None` disables destination binding in signed headers, making the scheme bypassable via relay attacks.\n\n**Problem**: When a node has a cryptographic identity (can sign/verify headers) but `public_host` is `None` (the default), `SignatureVerifier::verify_destination()` returns `Ok(())` unconditionally. An attacker who captures a valid signed request for nodeA can replay it against nodeB — the signature is valid, but nodeB doesn't check that the request was actually addressed to it.\n\n**Goal**: Make destination verification **secure by default** — refuse to start a node with identity but no `public_host`, unless the operator explicitly opts in to insecure mode.\n\n## Changes\n\n### 1. Add `allow_insecure_destination` config field\n\n**File**: `apps/node/src/config.rs`\n\n- Add `allow_insecure_destination: bool` to `NodeConfig` (default `false`, `serde(default)`)\n- Add `--allow-insecure-destination` CLI arg and `REME_NODE_ALLOW_INSECURE_DESTINATION` env var\n- Wire through config resolution (same pattern as other bool fields)\n\n### 2. Enforce at startup in `main.rs`\n\n**File**: `apps/node/src/main.rs` (around line 154-162)\n\nReplace the current warn-only block with enforcement logic:\n\n```\nif identity.is_some() && config.public_host.is_none() {\n    if config.allow_insecure_destination {\n        warn!(\"public_host not configured — signature destination verification DISABLED\");\n        warn!(\"Signed requests will be accepted regardless of destination. This is insecure.\");\n    } else {\n        error!(\"Node has identity but public_host is not configured.\");\n        error!(\"Signature destination verification cannot work without public_host.\");\n        error!(\"Set public_host in config/CLI/env, or set allow_insecure_destination = true to proceed without it.\");\n        std::process::exit(1);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### 3. Update example config\n\n**File**: `apps/node/config.example.toml`\n\nAdd a comment near `public_host` explaining the enforcement, and add `allow_insecure_destination` (commented out):\n\n```toml\n# Required when identity_path is set. Without this, the node refuses to start.\n# Set allow_insecure_destination = true to override (NOT recommended for production).\npublic_host = \"node1.example.com:23003\"\n# allow_insecure_destination = false\n```\n\n### 4. Update tests\n\n**File**: `apps/node/src/signed_headers.rs`\n\n- Rename `test_no_public_host_accepts_any_destination` → `test_no_public_host_skips_destination_check` (clarify intent — the verifier itself still allows this; enforcement is at startup)\n- Add a doc comment explaining the verifier is intentionally permissive; startup validation is the enforcement layer\n\n**File**: `apps/node/src/config.rs` (test module)\n\n- Add test: default config has `allow_insecure_destination = false`\n- Add test: config with `allow_insecure_destination = true` deserializes correctly\n\n### 5. Out of scope (remains on #68)\n\nThese are part of the broader #68 issue but not this PR:\n- Replication cert pinning (TODO at `replication.rs:137`)\n- Replication peer identity verification (TODO at `replication.rs:142`)\n- SEC-M3: `HttpTransport` warn-but-proceed on HTTP/unpinned-HTTPS\n\n## Verification\n\n1. `cargo fmt --all -- --check`\n2. `cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings`\n3. `cargo test --workspace --all-features --all-targets`\n4. Manual: `cargo run --bin node` without `public_host` but with identity → should error and exit\n5. Manual: same with `--allow-insecure-destination` → should warn but start\n6. Manual: with `public_host` set → should start normally (no change)\n",
